<h2 class="text-center my-4">Cetaceans Found in Tubbataha Reef</h2>

<div class="text-center mb-4">
    <img src="https://encrypted-tbn0.gstatic.com/images?q=tbn:ANd9GcTYcR_sofdxwkWvWda_UV3t3v16ARatSAqeVw&s" alt="Cetaceans in Tubbataha Reef" class="img-fluid img-resize" />
</div>

<p class="mb-4">
    Tubbataha’s surrounding waters are part of the Sulu Sea, which provides a rich habitat for many cetacean species. Commonly sighted cetaceans in the area include dolphins and whales, each contributing to the health of the marine ecosystem.
</p>

<h3 class="text-center my-4">Common Cetacean Species in Tubbataha Reef</h3>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">1. Spinner Dolphins (Stenella longirostris)</h4>
    <ul>
        <div class="text-center mb-4">
            <img src="https://oceana.org/wp-content/uploads/sites/18/spinner_dolphins-scaled.jpg" alt="Spinner Dolphins" class="img-fluid img-resize" />
        </div>
        <li>Known for their acrobatic spinning behavior when they leap out of the water.</li>
        <li>Often seen in pods, sometimes numbering in the hundreds.</li>
    </ul>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">2. Bottlenose Dolphins (Tursiops truncatus)</h4>
    <ul>
        <div class="text-center mb-4">
            <img src="https://cff2.earth.com/uploads/2023/11/30185539/bottlenose-dolphin_1medium-1400x850.jpg" alt="Bottlenose Dolphins" class="img-fluid img-resize" />
        </div>
        <li>Sociable and intelligent, they are one of the most recognized dolphin species.</li>
    </ul>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">3. Risso's Dolphins (Grampus griseus)</h4>
    <ul>
        <div class="text-center mb-4">
            <img src="https://encrypted-tbn0.gstatic.com/images?q=tbn:ANd9GcSFTP4YJp6VRajwWfbAhe-Wzrgx96RpZPeuAA&s" alt="Risso's Dolphins" class="img-fluid img-resize" />
        </div>
        <li>Identified by their gray coloration and scars on their bodies.</li>
    </ul>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">4. Short-finned Pilot Whales (Globicephala macrorhynchus)</h4>
    <ul>
        <div class="text-center mb-4">
            <img src="https://www.natureplprints.com/p/729/short-finned-pilot-whales-globicephala-18852424.jpg.webp" alt="Short-finned Pilot Whales" class="img-fluid img-resize" />
        </div>
        <li>Deep-diving cetaceans often seen in groups, they primarily feed on squid.</li>
    </ul>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">5. Sperm Whales (Physeter macrocephalus)</h4>
    <ul>
        <div class="text-center mb-4">
            <img src="https://encrypted-tbn0.gstatic.com/images?q=tbn:ANd9GcQRo42GTt_gynWRLvQwCZNXPVgU3vlkRDIs3w&s" alt="Sperm Whales" class="img-fluid img-resize" />
        </div>
        <li>The largest toothed whales, capable of diving to great depths in search of squid.</li>
    </ul>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">6. Bryde's Whales (Balaenoptera edeni)</h4>
    <ul>
        <div class="text-center mb-4">
            <img src="https://defendersofwildlife-360365372.imgix.net/sites/default/files/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/brydes-whale-Nathan-Meadows.jpg?fit=max&ixlib=php-4.1.0&w=2000" alt="Bryde's Whales" class="img-fluid img-resize" />
        </div>
        <li>Baleen whales that feed on small fish and krill, often seen surfacing in the area.</li>
    </ul>
</section>

<h3 class="text-center my-4">Interesting Facts About Cetaceans</h3>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">1. Cetaceans' Role in the Ecosystem</h4>
    <p>They play a critical role in nutrient cycling in marine ecosystems, contributing to the health of coral reefs like Tubbataha.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">2. High Diversity</h4>
    <p>The diversity of cetaceans in Tubbataha reflects the health and richness of the marine environment in the Sulu Sea.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">3. Unique Behavior</h4>
    <p>Spinner dolphins' spins and social behaviors are often a tourist highlight, and their patterns offer insight into marine mammal communication and group dynamics.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">4. Migratory Patterns</h4>
    <p>Some cetaceans, like sperm whales, migrate through the area seasonally, making Tubbataha an important waypoint.</p>
</section>

<h3 class="text-center my-4">Conservation Practices to Protect Cetaceans</h3>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">1. Reduce Plastic Use</h4>
    <p>Plastics often end up in the ocean, endangering marine life. Use reusable bags, bottles, and utensils.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">2. Participate in Beach Cleanups</h4>
    <p>Organized cleanups help reduce marine debris that can harm cetaceans.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">3. Support Sustainable Tourism</h4>
    <p>Choose eco-certified tour operators and follow guidelines to avoid disturbing marine life.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">4. Educate Others</h4>
    <p>Raise awareness about the importance of cetaceans and Tubbataha Reef conservation.</p>
</section>

<h3 class="text-center my-4">Challenges in Cetacean Conservation</h3>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">1. Bycatch in Fisheries</h4>
    <p>Cetaceans often get entangled in fishing nets, leading to injury or death.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">2. Climate Change</h4>
    <p>Ocean warming and acidification threaten cetaceans' food sources and habitats.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">3. Marine Pollution</h4>
    <p>Chemical spills and plastic pollution impact cetaceans' health and environment.</p>
</section>

